{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413121"},"attributes":{"position":5,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T07:56:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T07:56:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13024"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:11:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13024"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"13024","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13024"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.73,0.06,0.01,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5461"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41181"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5461"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13024"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25900"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"1947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9263"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10569"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43379"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41181"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents with a five-week history of persistent lower back pain and stiffness. He first noticed the symptoms 12 months ago but the pain was mild, intermittent and attributed to over-exercising at the gym. However, it is now more persistent and is interfering with his occupation as a plumber. The pain is most severe when he first wakes up in the morning, and gradually improves throughout the day. He cannot recall any trauma or injury to his back. He reports no pain or numbness in the lower extremities. His bowel and bladder function is unchanged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the patient appears comfortable at rest but struggles to reach down and undo his shoelaces. He has very minimal tenderness on palpation of his lower back. Neurological examination of his lower limbs is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn X-ray of the sacroiliac joints shows bilateral joint sclerosis and possible small erosions of the right sided sacroiliac joint.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory tests reveal the following:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein (CRP): 30 mg/L (0-5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR): 25 mm/hr (0-10)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Local heat therapy","Ibuprofen","Epidural steroid injection","Oxycodone","Methotrexate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBack pain that improves with exercise, but worsens with rest in an otherwise healthy patient raises the possibility of ankylosing spondylitis (AS). AS is a seronegative spondyloarthropathy, often associated with the HLA-B27 genotype. It is three times more common in males than females. Although inflammatory back pain is the most common manifestation of AS, it can manifest any of the other shared clinical features of the seronegative spondyloarthropathies e.g. peripheral arthritis, dactylitis, enthesitis, psoriasis, anterior uveitis and inflammatory bowel disease. Additionally, AS can be complicated by interstitial lung disease and aortic regurgitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFirst-line treatment for AS is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eibuprofen\u003C/strong\u003E, which can help reduce inflammation and relieve pain. However, it is important to consider any contraindications or potential side effects of NSAIDs before initiating treatment. If NSAIDs do not adequately control symptoms, then biologic therapies (such as TNF inhibitors or IL-17 inhibitors) would be the next line of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELocal heat therapy\u003C/strong\u003E involves applying heat to the affected area to help relax muscles and alleviate pain. It can be in the form of hot packs, warm showers, or heating pads. Heat therapy can improve blood circulation, reduce muscle stiffness, and provide temporary pain relief. It is a conservative measure that can be used as part of the initial management of low back pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpidural steroid injection\u003C/strong\u003E are invasive, have limited evidence for use in sacroiliitis and would not typically be a first line option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOpioid analgesics such as \u003Cstrong\u003Eoxycodone\u003C/strong\u003E do not have a role in the management of inflammatory back pain and are generally not recommended because they are ineffective, with side effects that outweigh the possible benefits. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConventional synthetic DMARDs such as \u003Cstrong\u003Emethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E are not effective for inflammatory spinal disease although they can be used to treat other manifestations such as peripheral arthritis, inflammatory bowel disease or psoriasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosing AS is of paramount importance as it enables early intervention, targeted therapy, patient education, and effective symptom management. An early AS diagnosis allows healthcare providers to tailor treatments to the specific disease, control inflammation, and prevent progression. Once diagnosed, the focus shifts to therapeutic options, including physical therapy, medication management, patient education, and lifestyle modifications. This multidisciplinary approach enhances patient well-being, quality of life, and the ability to manage AS effectively, minimizing the need for further investigation and concentrating on therapies that alleviate symptoms and slow disease progression.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["NSAIDs are first-line therapy for symptomatic ankylosing spondylitis patients."],"references":["The Royal Australian College of general Practitioners. Ankylosing spondylitis [Internet]. The Royal Australian College of general Practitioners; [cited 2023 Jun 10]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/november/ankylosing-spondylitis","Dau JD, Lee M, Ward MM, Gensler LS, Brown MA, Learch TJ, Diekman LA, Tahanan A, Rahbar MH, Weisman MH, Reveille JD. Opioid analgesic use in patients with ankylosing spondylitis: an analysis of the prospective study of outcomes in an ankylosing spondylitis cohort. The Journal of rheumatology. 2018 Feb 1;45(2):188-94. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5805598/#:~:text=Opioid%20analgesics%20may%20be%20prescribed,unresponsive%20to%20anti%2Drheumatic%20treatment."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25900"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13024"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25900"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-04T07:31:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-04T07:31:11+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5461"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41181"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups"